- low annotation burden;
- principal types in the classic setting (every well-typed program has a most-general type);
- excellent for ML-style functional cores (no subtyping, simple side-effect story);
- conceptually small enough for an early compiler — Algorithm W is a few hundred lines of code in most implementations.

HM's predictability comes from restricting the type structure. Costs accumulate when a language wants more:

- effects require value restriction or another discipline (OCaml's value restriction is the canonical pragmatic answer);
- subtyping complicates principality — F<: loses HM-style inference; algebraic subtyping (`data/mlsub-algebraic-subtyping`) recovers it by restricting the type lattice;
- higher-rank polymorphism requires annotations or bidirectional methods (`data/higher-rank-polymorphism`);
- type classes, GADTs, type families, and associated types require a richer constraint solver (`data/constraint-based-typing`).

For language designers, the rule of thumb is: **start with HM if the language is functional and effect-light; switch to bidirectional + constraint-based when the type system grows beyond rank-1 polymorphism**.
